</p>
						
						<p><div class="item">
<h2><a class="listing" style="link" href="/en/Dossiers/S-T-Issues/Dryland-agriculture/Related-developments/Agriculture-Namibia-Turning-to-wild-bean-for-protein" title="Agriculture Namibia: Turning to wild bean for protein" alt="link">Agriculture Namibia: Turning to wild bean for protein</a></h2>

	
					<p>Namibia is one of the driest countries in sub-Saharan Africa. Its two deserts – the Namib and the Kalahari – are expanding annually. Poor soils and a shortage of water are limiting factors for farmers. The University of Namibia has begun experimental cultivation of the marama bean, (Tylosema esculentum) - a pod-bearing perennial that grows wild across Southern Africa and that can grow under extreme dry conditions. The research process itself also benefits the building of plant-breeding skills and the programme is expected to train many scientists over the projected 18 year period that it will run,&quot; says Chimwamurombe. (Source: IPS, 1 Apr 2010)</p>
							<p><span class="date">26/04/2010</span></p>
	<div class="cnt">
	<a class="link" href="/en/Dossiers/S-T-Issues/Dryland-agriculture/Related-developments/Agriculture-Namibia-Turning-to-wild-bean-for-protein">Read more...</a>
